-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; back=
ground-color: #ccc;">tender offer announcement</a>. Credit Suisse has about=
 $1.9 billion of 1% U.S. dollar notes due in about six weeks. In six weeks,=
 it will have to pay those bonds off at 100 cents on the dollar. Yesterday =
they traded at 92.6 cents on the dollar, a yield of about 60%. Today Credit=
 Suisse is offering to buy them at 98 cents on the dollar, a yield of about=
 19%.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #0000=
00; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bott=
om-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: =
transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0In general if you are a global megabank and you can invest safely=
 in a short-term investment that yields 19%, you should. It also has $923 m=
illion of 0.495% notes due next February. Those traded yesterday at 83.8 ce=
nts on the dollar. Credit Suisse is offering to buy them at 90, a yield of =
about 13%.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Bloomberg News <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
oombergbusiness.com/click/30857809.259423/aHR0cHM6Ly9uZXdzLmJsb29tYmVyZ2xhd=
y5jb20vYmFua3J1cHRjeS1sYXcvY3JlZGl0LXN1aXNzZS1vZmZlcnMtdG8tYnV5LWJhY2stZGVi=
dC1mb3ItYWJvdXQtMy1iaWxsaW9uLWZyYW5jcw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB60669d01" i=
temprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"co=
lor: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; b=
order-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: =
#ccc;">  reports</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse Group AG=C2=A0is poised to save =
about $70 million with its plan to buy back debt, as it looks to counter a =
collapse in market confidence.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The bank proposed buying back 3 billion francs=
 ($3.2 billion) of bonds at a discount, which would enable it to save on th=
e cost of redeeming those notes later.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">It=E2=80=99s offering to buy back 14 dollar- a=
nd euro-denominated senior debt=C2=A0securities, according to a=C2=A0statem=
ent=C2=A0on Thursday in which it also said it would tap a=C2=A0Swiss Nation=
al Bank=C2=A0liquidity facility for as much as 50 billion francs. The trans=
actions =E2=80=9Callow us to take advantage of current trading levels to re=
purchase debt at attractive prices=E2=80=9D as well as manage interest expe=
nse, it said in a statement.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But surely Credit Suisse would be thrilled to =
have the tender offer fail =E2=80=94=C2=A0to have no one show up to sell bo=
nds at these prices =E2=80=94 and miss out on saving the $70 million. Seven=
ty million dollars is pocket change; Credit Suisse posted a <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30857809.259423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc=
2VjLmdvdi9peD9kb2M9L0FyY2hpdmVzL2VkZ2FyL2RhdGEvMDAwMTE1OTUxMC8wMDAxMzcwMzY4=
MjMwMDAwMjYvY3MtMjAyMjEyMzEuaHRtI0lkMDAxMzEwNzQy/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB8=
d05b19e" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" s=
tyle=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-wid=
th: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgrou=
nd-color: #ccc;"> net loss of CHF 7.3=C2=A0billion</a> last year. If its sh=
ort-term debt rallies enough that it is no longer able to buy back its one-=
month bonds at a 19% yield, that means that its one-month debt is no longer=
 trading at a 19% yield. That=E2=80=99s way better than saving $70 million!=
 Global banks live or die by their access to credit markets, and they don=
=E2=80=99t live all that long if their debt trades at distressed levels.=C2=
=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Credit Suisse=E2=80=99s main goal right now is=
 to convince funding markets that everything is fine. If you want to convin=
ce traders of something, the best evidence is a trade. The market is tellin=
g Credit Suisse that its debt is distressed. Credit Suisse wants to tell th=
e market that it isn=E2=80=99t, that everything is fine. The way to do that=
 is with price: The market says =E2=80=9CCredit Suisse=E2=80=99s debt is di=
stressed and only worth 84 cents on the dollar,=E2=80=9D and Credit Suisse =
says =E2=80=9Coh yeah? I=E2=80=99ll pay you 90.=E2=80=9D It is a show of co=
nfidence from Credit Suisse, backed up by a show of confidence from the SNB=
. Perhaps it will help.</p>
