<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">First Republic</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here are two Wall Street Journal stories. One =
<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/30857809.259423/aH=
R0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy9qcG1vcmdhbi1tb3JnYW4tc3RhbmxleS1hbmQtb=
3RoZXJzLWluLXRhbGtzLXRvLWJvbHN0ZXItZmlyc3QtcmVwdWJsaWMtNGY5ZWViNzY_bW9kPWJy=
ZWFraW5nbmV3cw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBbcea4fff" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" it=
emscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decor=
ation: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000=
000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> is about First R=
epublic Bank</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">JPMorgan Chase &amp; Co., Morgan Stanley and s=
everal other big banks are discussing a potential deal with First Republic =
Bank that could include a sizable capital infusion to shore up the beleague=
red lender, people familiar with the matter said.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">First Republic is working on various potential=
 options including a capital raise that could take various forms, the peopl=
e said. A full takeover is also a possibility, though some of the people ca=
utioned that looks unlikely at this point.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The situation is fluid and whether a deal come=
s together and what it might look like is still highly uncertain. Any deal =
would need the blessing of regulators and will be driven at least in part b=
y the bank=E2=80=99s highly volatile stock. First Republic=E2=80=99s stock =
has been pummeled for days and fell another 31% Thursday morning over conce=
rns about the bank=E2=80=99s health in the wake of the collapse of Silicon =
Valley Bank.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The other <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombe=
rgbusiness.com/click/30857809.259423/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9hcnRpY2xlcy=
9ob3ctZ29sZG1hbnMtcGxhbi10by1zaG9yZS11cC1zaWxpY29uLXZhbGxleS1iYW5rLWNydW1ib=
GVkLTk2YmI0NGJi/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5ceba8df" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" i=
temscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-deco=
ration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #00=
0000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;"> is about Silico=
n Valley Bank</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVB executives came to Goldman with the rough =
outlines of a plan to raise capital. Two private-equity firms, General Atla=
ntic and Warburg Pincus LLC, were on the bank=E2=80=99s list of possible in=
vestors. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Goldman pitched a hybrid public-private share =
sale: The firm would find enough investors to fully fund a $2.25 billion de=
al but would also offer the public an opportunity to buy shares at the same=
 price. =E2=80=A6 [Warburg backed out, and]=C2=A0Goldman decided the only o=
ption was a public share offering anchored by General Atlantic. SVB executi=
ves signed off on the plan. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVB=E2=80=99s stock at first fell around 8% in=
 aftermarket hours [on March 8, when the capital raise was launched], not a=
s steep a drop as feared, and Goldman=E2=80=99s bankers received many order=
s to buy shares. =E2=80=A6=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVB shares tanked when the market opened on Ma=
rch 9, prompting customers to pull their deposits. It was the beginning of =
a downward spiral: As news of the deposit run spread, the shares fell furth=
er, prompting more customers to yank their money. The stock closed down mor=
e than 60%.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Still, the deal wasn=E2=80=99t dead yet. Goldm=
an had lined up a slate of investors at $95 a share, about $11 less than th=
e day=E2=80=99s closing price.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">At around 5 p.m., Goldman bankers got a report=
 on SVB=E2=80=99s deposit outflows.=C2=A0</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVB=E2=80=99s lawyers at Sullivan &amp; Cromwe=
ll LLP said the deal couldn=E2=80=99t go forward without a disclosure about=
 the deposit losses. Goldman abandoned the deal. The Federal Deposit Insura=
nce Corp. seized SVB before it could open the next morning.=C2=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">SVB=E2=80=99s current share price is a mystery=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0the stock hasn=E2=80=99t traded since Thursday =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0but it is probably zero. The deal was launched with a stock price of $26=
7.83, it was about to price at $95, but then the lawyers decided it couldn=
=E2=80=99t price without revealing more details about the bank run, which w=
ould presumably lead to a much lower price. The next day, the value of the =
stock was zero.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">How does the <em>next </em>troubled regional b=
ank capital raise go? First Republic=E2=80=99s stock closed at $123.22 two =
weeks ago and=C2=A0$31.16 yesterday. It lost about $17 billion of market ca=
pitalization in two weeks. If JPMorgan calls you up and says =E2=80=9Cwe ar=
e trying to get a couple billion dollars of capital into First Republic, ar=
e you in,=E2=80=9D at what=C2=A0<em>price=C2=A0</em>are you in? The bid-ask=
 seems wide:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If they get a deal done at $20, or $2=
5, or some other reasonable-ish price, then the buyers will probably do wel=
l? I mean, not investing advice, and what do I know, but basically this sto=
ck is trading at pretty depressed prices because of worries about the bank =
going under. If they raise two yards of capital, those fears will be allaye=
d, and the stock might rip back up. You could multiply your investment in a=
 week.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">If they don=E2=80=99t get a=
 deal done, I am sorry, but the very highly publicized recent precedent is =
that the stock goes to zero in a day.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">So First Republic=E2=80=99s pitch to investors=
 is =E2=80=9Cif you buy the stock at $25 it will go to $50 in short order, =
so buy it at $25,=E2=80=9D and the investors=E2=80=99 response might reason=
ably be =E2=80=9Cif we=C2=A0<em>don=E2=80=99t=C2=A0</em>buy the stock at $2=
5 it will go to zero in short order, so we=E2=80=99ll buy it for $1,=E2=80=
=9D and that=E2=80=99s not very helpful.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bl=
