 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-=
color: #ccc;"> not happy with the Silicon Valley Bank bailout</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One senior eurozone official described their s=
hock at the =E2=80=9Ctotal and utter incompetence=E2=80=9D of US authoritie=
s, particularly after a decade and a half of =E2=80=9Clong and boring meeti=
ngs=E2=80=9D with Americans advocating an end to bailouts.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Europe=E2=80=99s supervisors are particularly =
irate at the US decision to break with its own standard of guaranteeing onl=
y the first $250,000 of deposits by invoking a =E2=80=9Csystemic risk excep=
tion=E2=80=9D =E2=80=94 despite claiming the California-based lender was to=
o small to face rules aimed at preventing a rerun of the 2008 global financ=
ial crisis.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CThis is the US version of the small V=
enetian banks,=E2=80=9D said one French policy expert, referring to the US=
=E2=80=99s criticism of Europe=E2=80=99s handling of the Monte dei Paschi d=
ebacle. =E2=80=9CYou are always systemic for somebody.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">=E2=80=9CFrom a financial stability perspectiv=
e, they really killed a fly with a sledgehammer,=E2=80=9D said Nicolas V=C3=
=A9ron, a regulation expert at the Washington think-tank the Peterson Insti=
tute. Designating SVB as systemic was, V=C3=A9ron added, a =E2=80=9Cvery qu=
estionable=E2=80=9D decision that set a dangerous precedent for further bai=
louts of uninsured deposits.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">A former senior UK policymaker who helped nego=
tiate global standards for bank resolution described the SVB handling as a =
=E2=80=9Cdisaster=E2=80=9D.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The 2008 crisis triggered a sea change in how =
to handle the collapse of banks, with policymakers meeting often at the Bas=
el-based headquarters of the Bank for International Settlements to create r=
egimes designed to minimise the wider fallout from failures.</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I can find nothing to object to in this critic=
ism. Yes, absolutely, after 2008 global regulators tried to create regimes =
to minimize the systemic risks of big banks, and US regulators supervised r=
egional banks like SVB with a light touch specifically because our politica=
l system concluded that those banks were=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</em>systemicall=
y important, and then at the first sign of trouble at SVB the US=C2=A0<em>d=
id=C2=A0</em>conclude it was systemically important and rushed to implement=
 a giant bailout. =E2=80=9CKilled a fly with a sledgehammer=E2=80=9D seems =
right, as does =E2=80=9Clong and boring meetings=E2=80=9D for that matter.<=
/p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">That said, my gut instinct is that something l=
ike =E2=80=9Ctalk constantly about how you=E2=80=99ll never ever ever ever =
do bailouts, but then occasionally do a bailout=E2=80=9D is basically the r=
ight approach to bank regulation? As a matter of moral hazard and discourag=
ing bad risk-taking, you have to tell banks =E2=80=9Cwe would never bail yo=
u out,=E2=80=9D because then they will try to behave themselves. But then i=
f they <em>do=C2=A0</em>take bad risks, as a matter of not burning the hous=
e down, you bail them out anyway.=C2=A0</p>
